# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview of YANG

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

**YANG (Yet Another Next Generation)** is a standards-based, extensible **data modeling language** defined by the IETF in **RFC 6020** (initial release) and updated in **RFC 7950** (YANG 1.1). It is explicitly designed to model **configuration data, state data, Remote Procedure Calls (RPCs), and notifications** for network elements. In the IoT ecosystem, YANG is the de-facto modeling language used in conjunction with **NETCONF (RFC 6241)** and **RESTCONF (RFC 8040)** to enable programmatic, schema-driven management of heterogeneous IoT gateways, sensors, and network devices.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Syllabus Highlight:** YANG is taught as the *schema definition language* that gives semantic meaning to IoT device data. Without YANG, IoT data exchanged via NETCONF/RESTCONF would be unstructured XML/JSON with no validation or contract.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine a **smart home** where every device (smart bulb, thermostat, door lock) is manufactured by a different company. The bulb speaks a proprietary format, the thermostat another, and the door lock yet another. Your mobile app cannot uniformly control them.

Now imagine a **universal language** that every device MUST use to describe:
- What data fields it exposes (e.g., `brightness` for the bulb, `temperature` for the thermostat).
- What data types those fields have (integer, string, boolean).
- What values are allowed (range, enumerations).
- What operations can be performed (read, write, invoke).

**That universal language is YANG.** It is the *grammar book* or *blueprint* that device manufacturers write so that any controller can instantly understand how to communicate with the device — just like how HTML5 standardized how all browsers render web pages.

> [!NOTE]
> **Plain English Summary:** YANG = "A strict contract that tells controllers exactly what data an IoT device holds, in what format, and how it can be manipulated." It is to IoT devices what a **database schema** is to a relational database.

## 1.3 Physical Standards & Constants

| Parameter | Value / Standard |
|---|---|
| **YANG 1.0 RFC** | **RFC 6020** |
| **YANG 1.1 RFC** | **RFC 7950** |
| **Default Encoding** | **XML** (with NETCONF) and **JSON** (with RESTCONF) |
| **Transport Binding** | NETCONF over SSH, RESTCONF over HTTP/HTTPS |
| **Hierarchical Style** | **Tree-based, nested module** |
| **Path Expression** | **XPath-like** (subset) |
| **Module File Extension** | `.yang` |

> [!NOTE]
> YANG is **NOT a programming language**. It is a **modeling language** — it has no executable logic, only declarative schema definitions. Compilation produces a tree of nodes that can be serialized into XML or JSON.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The Operational Philosophy: Why YANG Exists

Traditional network management relied on **SNMP MIBs** (Management Information Bases) which had critical limitations:
- **Rigid typing** — limited primitive types.
- **No RPC modeling** — only GET/SET operations.
- **Poor human readability** of MIB modules.
- **No clear separation** of configuration vs. state data.

YANG was engineered to solve these problems by providing:
- A **rich type system** (built-in + derived types).
- Explicit modeling of **configuration, state, RPCs, and notifications**.
- **Human-readable syntax** with strict grammar (BNF defined in RFC).
- **Module reusability** via `import`, `include`, `augment`.

## 2.2 The YANG Module Structure (Anatomy)

Every YANG module follows a strict skeleton:

```
module <module-name> {
    yang-version 1.1;
    namespace "<urn:...">;
    prefix <prefix>;
    import <other-module> { prefix <p>; }
    organization "...";
    contact "...";
    description "...";
    revision <YYYY-MM-DD> { ... }
    // BODY: typedef, grouping, container, list, leaf, ...
}
```

## 2.3 The YANG Statement Hierarchy (Core Building Blocks)

YANG defines data as a **tree of nodes**. Every node is a statement. The principal node types are:

| Node Type | Purpose | KTU Exam Importance |
|---|---|---|
| `module` | Top-level container; declares module identity | High |
| `submodule` | A reusable fragment of a module | Medium |
| `container` | Groups related nodes (like a folder/struct) | Very High |
| `list` | An ordered/unordered collection of list entries keyed by a leaf | Very High |
| `leaf` | A single data value with a type (no children) | Very High |
| `leaf-list` | A sequence of leaf values (duplicates allowed) | High |
| `choice` / `case` | Mutual exclusion between subtrees | Medium |
| `grouping` | A reusable, inline-instantiable set of nodes | High |
| `uses` | Instantiates a `grouping` | High |
| `rpc` | Models a remote procedure call operation | High |
| `input` / `output` | Sub-statements of `rpc` | Medium |
| `notification` | Models an event message | High |
| `augment` | Extends an existing data tree with new nodes | Very High |
| `deviation` | Allows device-specific override of a module | Medium |
| `identity` | Globally unique, abstract identifier | Medium |
| `typedef` | Defines a new type derived from a base type | High |
| `refine` | Modifies nodes inherited from a `uses` | Low-Medium |
| `feature` | Conditional inclusion flag | Low |

## 2.4 The Built-In YANG Type System

YANG has a robust set of primitive types. The high-yield ones for KTU exams:

| Type | Description | Example Value |
|---|---|---|
| `uint8` | Unsigned 8-bit integer (range 0..255) | `42` |
| `uint16`, `uint32`, `uint64` | Unsigned integers of respective widths | `1000` |
| `int8`, `int16`, `int32`, `int64` | Signed integers | `-15` |
| `decimal64` | Fixed-precision decimal | `3.14` |
| `string` | UTF-8 string | `"hello"` |
| `boolean` | `true` or `false` | `true` |
| `enumeration` | User-defined set of named values | `"active"` |
| `bits` | Named bit positions | `"flag-a flag-b"` |
| `binary` | Base64-encoded binary | `"AAEC"` |
| `union` | A value belonging to one of several types | n/a |
| `leafref` | Reference to another leaf instance | `../id` |
| `instance-identifier` | Reference to a tree node | `/if:interfaces/...` |
| `identityref` | Reference to an `identity` | n/a |
| `empty` | Represents a presence; has no value | `null` |

> [!NOTE]
> **Key constraint:** YANG strings **cannot contain the null character** (`\u0000`) and all numerical types have a strictly defined **range and length** substatement. Range uses interval notation: `range "0..100"` or `range "min..max"` with conditions like `range "-50..0 \vert 10..20"`.

## 2.5 The XPath Subset for YANG Paths

YANG uses a subset of **XPath 1.0** for predicates in `path`, `must`, `when`, `leafref`, etc.

| XPath Axis / Function | YANG Use Case |
|---|---|
| `current()` | Refers to the node where the expression is defined |
| `../` | Move to the parent node |
| `/if:interfaces/interface[name='eth0']` | Absolute path with namespace prefix |
| `deref(...)` | Dereference a `leafref` to a target node |
| `count(...)` | Count of nodes in a node-set |
| `boolean(...)` | Convert expression to boolean |
| `not(...)` | Logical NOT |

## 2.6 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| # | Concept | YANG Construct | Notation / Example |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Module declaration | `module` | `module iot-sensor { ... }` |
| 2 | Namespace URI | URN string | `"urn:ktu:iot:sensor"` |
| 3 | Type derivation | `typedef` | `typedef percent { type uint8 { range "0..100"; } }` |
| 4 | Mandatory flag | `mandatory true;` | Forces client to provide value |
| 5 | Default value | `default "off";` | Applied if not configured |
| 6 | Key list | `key "id";` | Uniquely identifies list entries |
| 7 | Unique constraint | `unique "mac ip";` | Combination of leaves is unique |
| 8 | Path expression | `path` / `leafref` | `path "../../../name";` |
| 9 | Conditional validity | `when "../enabled='true';` | Node exists only if condition holds |
| 10 | Constraint | `must "string-length(.) > 0";` | XPath boolean must be true |
| 11 | Range of integer | `range "1..65535";` | Inclusive bounds |
| 12 | Pattern match | `pattern "[A-Z][a-zA-Z0-9]*";` | Regex over string |
| 13 | Sub-module include | `include` | Pulls a submodule into module |
| 14 | External module use | `import` | Pulls external module |
| 15 | Tree extension | `augment` | `augment /if:interfaces/interface { ... }` |
| 16 | Feature gate | `feature` | `if-feature "crypto";` |
| 17 | RPC input | `input { ... }` | Substatement of `rpc` |
| 18 | Notification | `notification` | Event definition |
| 19 | Data definition | `description` | Human-readable string |
| 20 | Reference | `reference` | Point to external doc |

> [!WARNING]
> In KTU theory answers, students often confuse `import` vs. `include`. **Remember:** `import` brings in an **external** module (different namespace), while `include` brings in a **submodule** (same namespace, same revision history).
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

This section presents an **exhaustive derivation of a complete YANG module** representing a generic IoT temperature sensor — building it from first principles, one block at a time. This is the type of model answer that earns full marks in KTU 14-mark design questions.

## 3.1 Engineering Specification (Design Goal)

We need to model an **IoT temperature sensor** with the following requirements:

1. A sensor has a **unique ID** (mandatory integer).
2. A sensor has a **location** (string, must match a pattern).
3. A sensor reports a **temperature reading** (decimal, signed, between $-40^\circ C$ and $125^\circ C$).
4. A sensor has an **enabled** status (boolean, defaults to `true`).
5. Readings must include a **timestamp**.
6. The module must be able to be **augmented** into a NETCONF `<interfaces>` tree.
7. The system must support an **RPC** to reset a sensor.
8. The system must emit a **notification** when temperature crosses a threshold.

## 3.2 Step 1 — Module Header (Identification Block)

```
module iot-temperature-sensor {
    yang-version 1.1;
    namespace "urn:ktu:iot:sensor:temperature";
    prefix temp-sensor;
    organization "KTU B.Tech IoT Course";
    contact "student@ktu.ac.in";
    description "Models an IoT temperature sensor compliant with NETCONF.";
    revision 2024-01-15 {
        description "Initial revision for KTU 2024 Scheme.";
    }
}
```

### Logical Derivation
- The `module` keyword opens the scope.
- `yang-version 1.1` is mandatory to use features like `anydata` and stricter `leafref`.
- `namespace` MUST be a globally unique URI; URN form is convention.
- `prefix temp-sensor` will prefix all our elements when serialized.
- `revision` date `2024-01-15` follows **ISO 8601** format `YYYY-MM-DD`.

## 3.3 Step 2 — Custom Type Definition (`typedef`)

```
typedef temperature-celsius {
    type decimal64 {
        fraction-digits 2;
        range "-40..125";
    }
    units "degrees Celsius";
    description "Industrial-grade temperature in Celsius.";
}
```

### Logical Derivation
We derive a new type `temperature-celsius` from the **built-in `decimal64`** primitive.
- The variable $f$ (fraction-digits) determines the precision:

$$
\text{precision} = 10^{-f} = 10^{-2} = 0.01 \;^\circ C
$$

- The range substatement enforces the physical sensor limit:

$$
T \in [-40, \; 125] \quad \text{where} \quad T \in \mathbb{R}
$$

- If $T < -40$ or $T > 125$, the **NETCONF server** MUST reject the `<edit-config>` with an error tagged `invalid-value`.

## 3.4 Step 3 — Reusable Grouping (`grouping` + `uses`)

```
grouping sensor-identity {
    leaf id {
        type uint32;
        mandatory true;
        description "Globally unique sensor identifier.";
    }
    leaf location {
        type string {
            length "1..64";
            pattern '[A-Z][a-zA-Z0-9_\-]{0,63}';
        }
        description "Physical location label.";
    }
}
```

The XPath pattern constraint:

$$
L = \text{location} \quad \text{must satisfy} \quad L[0] \in \{A..Z\}, \quad \vert L \vert \leq 64
$$

This grouping can be `uses`d anywhere we need a sensor identity.

## 3.5 Step 4 — The Top-Level Container

```
container sensors {
    list sensor {
        key "id";
        uses sensor-identity;
        leaf enabled {
            type boolean;
            default "true";
        }
        leaf last-reading {
            type temperature-celsius;
            config false;
            description "Operational state; not configurable.";
        }
        leaf last-updated {
            type yang:date-and-time;
            config false;
        }
        choice power-source {
            description "Mutually exclusive power source.";
            case battery {
                leaf battery-level {
                    type uint8 { range "0..100"; }
                    units "percent";
                }
            }
            case mains {
                leaf mains-voltage {
                    type decimal64 { fraction-digits 1; }
                    units "volts";
                }
            }
        }
        must "enabled = 'false' or last-reading <= 125.00" {
            error-message "Disabled sensors may not have readings > 125 C.";
        }
    }
}
```

### Logical Derivation of the `must` Constraint

The XPath `must` expression evaluates to a boolean. Let:

$$
E = \text{enabled}, \quad R = \text{last-reading}
$$

The constraint is:

$$
E = \text{false} \quad \lor \quad R \leq 125.00
$$

Truth table validation:

| $E$ | $R$ | $E = \text{false}$ | $R \leq 125$ | Result |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| true | 100.00 | false | true | **valid** |
| true | 130.00 | false | false | **invalid** |
| false | 130.00 | true | false | **valid** |

If the result is **false**, NETCONF returns `<rpc-error>` with our `error-message`.

## 3.6 Step 5 — RPC Definition

```
rpc reset-sensor {
    description "Force a hardware reset of a sensor.";
    input {
        leaf target-sensor-id {
            type leafref {
                path "/sensors/sensor/id";
            }
            mandatory true;
        }
    }
    output {
        leaf reset-status {
            type enumeration {
                enum ok;
                enum failed;
            }
        }
        leaf reset-timestamp {
            type yang:date-and-time;
        }
    }
}
```

### Logical Derivation of the `leafref` Path

The `leafref` type creates a pointer to an existing leaf. The path:

$$
P = \frac{\text{/sensors/sensor}}{id}
$$

The path is resolved at runtime. Let the user-supplied value be $v$:

$$
v \stackrel{?}{\in} \{ id_i \mid \text{for all sensor list entries} \}
$$

If $v$ does not exist in the set, the request is rejected.

## 3.7 Step 6 — Notification Definition

```
notification temperature-threshold-alert {
    description "Emitted when a sensor reading crosses a threshold.";
    leaf sensor-id {
        type leafref { path "/sensors/sensor/id"; }
        mandatory true;
    }
    leaf observed-temperature {
        type temperature-celsius;
        mandatory true;
    }
    leaf threshold-crossed {
        type enumeration {
            enum upper { value 1; }
            enum lower { value 0; }
        }
        mandatory true;
    }
    leaf event-time {
        type yang:date-and-time;
        mandatory true;
    }
}
```

The `event-time` MUST be a valid ISO 8601 timestamp:

$$
T_{\text{event}} = \text{YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS.s\pm HH:MM}
$$

## 3.8 Step 7 — Augmentation into External Tree

```
augment /if:interfaces/if:interface {
    when "if:type = 'ianaift:ethernetCsmacd'";
    leaf sensor-binding {
        type leafref { path "/sensors/sensor/id"; }
        description "Binds an interface to a temperature sensor.";
    }
}
```

### Logical Derivation

The augment extends the standard `ietf-interfaces` module. The `when` predicate activates it only when:

$$
\text{if:type} = \text{'ianaift:ethernetCsmacd'}
$$

This conditionality demonstrates the powerful **schema composition** of YANG.

## 3.9 Final Step — Complete Module (Concatenated Block)

The full compiled module (synthesizing steps 1–7) is the deliverable answer for a 14-mark question. The final tree structure produced is:

$$
\text{Module} \rightarrow \text{Container}(sensors) \rightarrow \text{List}(sensor) \rightarrow \{\text{Container}, \text{Leaf}, \text{Choice}\}
$$

The `leafref` cross-references form a directed acyclic graph (DAG) where every reference has a single source-of-truth node.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Exam Tip:** Always show the **serialized XML/JSON output** of your YANG model in the answer. For example, the sensors list serializes to:
> ```xml
> <sensors xmlns="urn:ktu:iot:sensor:temperature">
>     <sensor>
>         <id>1</id>
>         <location>Lab-A</location>
>         <enabled>true</enabled>
>         <last-reading>22.50</last-reading>
>         <last-updated>2024-06-01T10:00:00Z</last-updated>
>         <battery-level>85</battery-level>
>     </sensor>
> </sensors>
> ```
<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

