# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1 [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]
**Q: Define YANG. List any four built-in data types in YANG.**

**Model Answer:**

YANG (Yet Another Next Generation) is a **data modeling language** standardized by the IETF in **RFC 6020 / RFC 7950** used to model configuration data, state data, RPCs, and notifications for network elements managed via **NETCONF** and **RESTCONF**.

Four built-in types:
1. `uint8` — unsigned 8-bit integer.
2. `string` — UTF-8 character sequence.
3. `boolean` — `true` or `false`.
4. `enumeration` — user-defined set of named string values.

*(Other acceptable: `int32`, `decimal64`, `binary`, `bits`, `union`, `leafref`, `identityref`, `empty`.)*

---

### Question 2 [KTU University Exam – June 2024]
**Q: Differentiate between `container` and `list` in YANG with an example.**

**Model Answer:**

| Aspect | `container` | `list` |
|---|---|---|
| Cardinality | Exists at most once in the parent | Multiple instances allowed |
| Identification | No key required | MUST have a `key` leaf |
| Iteration | Accessed directly by name | Iterated using `list` entries |
| Example | `container system { leaf hostname { type string; } }` | `list user { key "uid"; leaf uid { type uint32; } }` |
| XML equivalent | Single XML element | Repeated XML elements |

A `list` is conceptually a **collection of `container`-like records**, each identified by a unique key.

---

## 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each)

### Question A (14 Marks) — KTU University Exam Pattern [May 2024]

**Q: (a)** Explain the architecture of YANG with a neat diagram. Discuss its role in IoT device management. **(7 marks)**

**Model Answer:**

YANG is structured as a **module** composed of a header (identifying block) and a body containing type definitions, groupings, data nodes (`container`, `list`, `leaf`), RPCs, and notifications. The module is processed by a **YANG compiler** (e.g., `pyang`, `yanglint`) to produce a schema tree, which is then used by NETCONF/RESTCONF clients and servers for validated data exchange.

*Diagram:* (see Section 4.1 — YANG Module Architecture Block Diagram above)

**Role in IoT Device Management:**
1. **Schema Validation:** Every `<config>` or `<rpc>` is validated against the YANG tree; invalid data is rejected at the protocol layer.
2. **Heterogeneity:** Different vendors' IoT devices expose a uniform, programmatic interface, eliminating proprietary APIs.
3. **Automation:** YANG models can be auto-converted to RESTCONF URIs, NETCONF XML, or gRPC protobuf, enabling CI/CD for IoT.
4. **Telemetry:** The `notification` construct models push-based event streams — perfect for IoT sensor alerts.
5. **Versioning:** The `revision` statement allows graceful module evolution.
6. **Discovery:** Standard modules like `ietf-system`, `ietf-interfaces` are well-known and discoverable.

**(b)** Write a complete YANG module to model a **smart street-light controller** that has a list of lights, each with an `id` (uint16), `brightness` (uint8, 0..100), `mode` (enumeration: `auto`, `manual`, `off`), and `last-power-consumption` (decimal64 in kWh, read-only). Include an RPC to manually toggle a specific light. **(7 marks)**

**Model Answer:**

```
module street-light-controller {
    yang-version 1.1;
    namespace "urn:ktu:iot:streetlight";
    prefix slc;
    organization "KTU Smart City Lab";
    contact "lab@ktu.ac.in";
    description "Models a smart street-light controller.";
    revision 2024-06-01 { description "Initial release."; }

    typedef power-kwh {
        type decimal64 { fraction-digits 3; }
        units "kWh";
    }

    rpc toggle-light {
        description "Manually toggles a light on or off.";
        input {
            leaf target-id {
                type leafref { path "/lights/light/id"; }
                mandatory true;
            }
            leaf desired-state {
                type enumeration {
                    enum on;
                    enum off;
                }
                mandatory true;
            }
        }
        output {
            leaf toggle-result {
                type enumeration { enum success; enum failure; }
            }
        }
    }

    container lights {
        list light {
            key "id";
            leaf id {
                type uint16;
                description "Unique street-light ID.";
            }
            leaf brightness {
                type uint8 { range "0..100"; }
                units "percent";
                default 50;
            }
            leaf mode {
                type enumeration {
                    enum auto;
                    enum manual;
                    enum off;
                }
                default auto;
            }
            leaf last-power-consumption {
                type power-kwh;
                config false;
                description "Read-only operational state.";
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**Explanation of key constructs:**
- `key "id"` ensures each `light` is uniquely identified.
- `config false` on `last-power-consumption` makes it a state-only leaf — clients cannot write to it via `<edit-config>`.
- The `leafref` in the RPC input ensures the `target-id` MUST exist in the operational data tree, preventing invalid commands.
- The `range "0..100"` constrains `brightness` to a valid percentage:

$$
B \in [0, 100], \quad B \in \mathbb{Z}
$$

---

### Question B (14 Marks) — Alternative Internal Choice [KTU Pattern]

**Q: (a)** With a suitable example, explain the use of `grouping`, `uses`, `augment`, and `refine` statements in YANG. **(7 marks)**

**Model Answer:**

- **`grouping`:** Defines a named, reusable set of nodes. Example:

  ```
  grouping interface-common {
      leaf name { type string; }
      leaf mtu  { type uint16 { range "68..9000"; } }
  }
  ```

- **`uses`:** Instantiates a grouping. Example:

  ```
  container ports {
      uses interface-common;
  }
  ```

  This is equivalent to inlining the `name` and `mtu` leaves inside `ports`.

- **`augment`:** Adds new nodes to an existing data tree. Example — extending `ietf-interfaces`:

  ```
  augment /if:interfaces/if:interface {
      leaf optical-power-dbm { type decimal64 { fraction-digits 2; } units "dBm"; }
  }
  ```

- **`refine`:** Modifies a node inherited from a `uses`. Example:

  ```
  uses interface-common {
      refine mtu {
          default 1500;
          description "Overridden default for Ethernet.";
      }
  }
  ```

**Comparison table:**

| Statement | Purpose | Operates On |
|---|---|---|
| `grouping` | Define a reusable template | Module / submodule |
| `uses` | Instantiate a grouping | Any data definition |
| `augment` | Extend a data tree (often external) | Tree of a module |
| `refine` | Modify a substatement of a `uses`d node | A `uses` reference |

**(b)** Explain `leafref`, `must`, and `when` constraints in YANG with examples. How do they enforce data integrity? **(7 marks)**

**Model Answer:**

- **`leafref`:** Pointer to another leaf. Enforces referential integrity.

  ```
  leaf interface-name {
      type leafref { path "/if:interfaces/if:interface/if:name"; }
  }
  ```

- **`must`:** XPath boolean constraint. If it evaluates to `false`, validation fails.

  ```
  leaf shutdown-time {
      type yang:date-and-time;
      must ". > current()/../start-time" {
          error-message "shutdown must be after start.";
      }
  }
  ```

- **`when`:** Conditional existence. A node is present in the tree only if the XPath is true.

  ```
  container dhcp {
      when "addressing = 'dynamic'";
      leaf lease-time { type uint32; units "seconds"; }
  }
  ```

**Data Integrity Enforcement:**

| Mechanism | Integrity Type |
|---|---|
| `type` + `range` / `pattern` / `length` | **Domain** integrity (valid values) |
| `mandatory true` | **Not-null** integrity |
| `unique` | **Entity** integrity (no duplicate composite keys) |
| `leafref` | **Referential** integrity (no orphan pointers) |
| `must` | **Semantic** integrity (business rules) |
| `when` | **Conditional** integrity (presence rules) |

Together these transforms YANG from a mere schema into a **contract-enforcing data-definition language** suitable for mission-critical IoT infrastructure.

