## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common places where KTU students lose marks on YANG questions:**
> 1. **Forgetting the `key` substatement** in a `list` — a list without a key is a syntax error. Always include `key "id";`.
> 2. **Confusing `config false` with `read-only`** — YANG uses `config false;` to mark a state leaf. There is no `read-only` keyword.
> 3. **Not declaring `yang-version 1.1;`** — without it, advanced features like `anydata`, `anyxml` enhancements, and stricter `leafref` semantics are not permitted.
> 4. **Using `|` for ranges in a markdown table answer** — the range uses space-separated intervals joined by `|` *inside YANG code*, but in theory answers, write it as `"0..100"` or `"min..max"`. Also remember the YANG union range form: `"-50..0 | 10..20"` with a **space** around the `|`.
> 5. **Forgetting the `mandatory true;` for `input`/`output` leaves** — students often declare RPC input parameters but omit `mandatory`, which leads to ambiguous behavior. Be explicit.
> 6. **Mixing up `import` vs `include`** — `import` is for an **external, separately-namespaced** module; `include` is for a **submodule** of the same module family.
> 7. **Not drawing the tree structure** — a 14-mark question on YANG almost always requires a **diagrammatic tree view** in addition to the `.yang` code. Always include one.

