## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **YANG** = Yet Another Next Generation, defined in **RFC 6020 (1.0)** and **RFC 7950 (1.1)**.
- YANG models **configuration, state, RPCs, and notifications** — it is **declarative, not procedural**.
- The **module** is the top-level unit. It is identified by a **URN namespace**, a **prefix**, a **revision date**, and **organization/contact metadata**.
- Core node types: `container`, `list`, `leaf`, `leaf-list`, `choice`, `case`, `grouping`, `uses`, `rpc`, `notification`, `augment`, `deviation`, `identity`, `typedef`, `feature`.
- **Built-in types:** `uint8/16/32/64`, `int8/16/32/64`, `decimal64`, `string`, `boolean`, `enumeration`, `bits`, `binary`, `union`, `leafref`, `instance-identifier`, `identityref`, `empty`.
- A `list` MUST have a `key`. A leaf of type `leafref` MUST resolve to an existing node. A node with `config false` is read-only.
- `must` evaluates an **XPath boolean**; `when` is a **conditional existence** predicate.
- YANG is paired with **NETCONF (over SSH, XML)** and **RESTCONF (over HTTP/HTTPS, JSON)**.
- `import` = external module; `include` = submodule. `augment` extends a data tree; `refine` modifies a `uses`d node.
- YANG is validated by tools like **`pyang`** and **`yanglint`**; errors are reported as NETCONF `<rpc-error>` elements.
- In the IoT domain, YANG enables **schema-driven, vendor-neutral, automated device management** — the foundation of Software-Defined IoT.
